data.content:
These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:

**1. `&&` with `dynamic` operand (DynamicOps.cs)**

C# 15 changed how short-circuit operators (`&&`/`||`) interact with `dynamic` operands. The compiler now **statically binds** `operator true`/`false` on the non-dynamic operand to determine short-circuiting, rather than deferring entirely to the runtime. With `IFilter` declaring static `operator true`/`false` at the interface level, this static resolution now fails or conflicts when paired with a `dynamic` right-hand side.

**Fix:** Avoid mixing static interface operators with `dynamic` in short-circuit expressions. Either:
```csharp
// Option A: cast away dynamic
var combined = left & (IFilter)right;

// Option B: use explicit two-step evaluation
if (left)
{
    var combined = left & right;
}
```

**2. `ref readonly` lambda return (RefHelper.cs — CS0518)**

C# 15 changed how `ref readonly` return types on lambdas are encoded in metadata — the compiler now requires `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RequiresLocationAttribute` to be available. If your target framework version doesn't include this type, you get **CS0518** ("predefined type is not defined or imported").

**Fix:** Either:
- Update your target framework / runtime packages to the version that ships `RequiresLocationAttribute`, or
- Polyfill it by declaring the attribute yourself:
```csharp
namespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices
{
    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Parameter, Inherited = false)]
    internal sealed class RequiresLocationAttribute : Attribute { }
}
```

Both are **source-breaking changes** introduced in the C# 15 compiler — existing valid code stops compiling without source or dependency updates.
